,"1487":"1487","1520":"1520","1475":"1475","1540":"1540","1460":"1460","about 1475":"okolo 1475","1480":"1480","7 Dec 1487":"7. prosince 1487","1490":"1490","Ireland":"Irsko","Thomond, Ireland":"County Clare, Irsko","Castle Chomhaid, Burren, Thomond, Ireland":"Boirinn, County Clare, Irsko","Rathkeale, Munster, Ierland":"Munster, Irsko"},"da":{"1460–1503":"1460–1503","1520–Male":"1520–Afdød","–Male":"Afdød","1460–1487":"1460–1487","1475–1540":"1475–1540","1490–Male":"1490–Afdød","1503":"1503","1487":"1487","1520":"1520","1475":"1475","1540":"1540","1460":"1460","about 1475":"omkring 1475","1480":"1480","7 Dec 1487":"7. december 1487","1490":"1490","Ireland":"Irland","Thomond, Ireland":"County Clare, Irland","Castle Chomhaid, Burren, Thomond, Ireland":"Boirinn, County Clare, Irland","Rathkeale, Munster, Ierland":"Munster, Irland"},"nl":{"1460–1503":"1460–1503","1520–Male":"1520–Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","1460–1487":"1460–1487","1475–1540":"1475–1540","1490–Male":"1490–Overleden","1503":"1503","1487":"1487","1520":"1520","1475":"1475","1540":"1540","1460":"1460","about 1475":"circa 1475","1480":"1480","7 Dec 1487":"7 december 1487","1490":"1490","Ireland":"Ierland","Thomond, Ireland":"County Clare, Ierland","Castle Chomhaid, Burren, Thomond, Ireland":"Boirinn, County Clare, Ierland","Rathkeale, Munster, Ierland":"Munster, Ierland"},"en":{"1460–1503":"1460–1503","1520–Male":"1520–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1460–1487":"1460–1487","1475–1540":"1475–1540","1490–Male":"1490–Deceased","1503":"1503","1487":"1487","1520":"1520","1475":"1475","1540":"1540","1460":"1460","about 1475":"about 1475","1480":"1480","7 Dec 1487":"7 December 1487","1490":"1490","Ireland":"Ireland","Thomond, Ireland":"County Clare, Ireland","Castle Chomhaid, Burren, Thomond, Ireland":"Boirinn, County Clare, Ireland","Rathkeale, Munster, Ierland":"Munster, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"O'Brian","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Liam.","Irish: variant of   O'Brien  ."],"variants":[{"name":"O'Brien","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Dermot, Liam, Brigid, Declan, Donovan, John Patrick, Kieran, Colm, Donal, Brennan, Caitlin.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Briain</b> ‘descendant of <i>Brian</i>’, a personal name probably based on the element <i>bre-</i> ‘hill’, with the transferred sense ‘eminence’, i.e. ‘exalted one’. See also   Bryan  . In Ireland there has also been some confusion with   O'Byrne   (see   Byrne  ).","History: This name is borne in particular by one of the greatest of Irish septs, descendants of Brian Boru, who rose to the high kingship of Ireland in 1002."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Maud O'Brian was born in 1460, in Boirinn, County Clare, Ireland as the daughter of Teige O'Brien. She married James Fitzgerald in 1480, in County Clare, Ireland. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1503, at the age of 43."},"et":{"1460–1503":"1460–1503","1520–Male":"1520–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1460–1487":"1460–1487","1475–1540":"1475–1540","1490–Male":"1490–Surnud","1503":"1503","1487":"1487","1520":"1520","1475":"1475","1540":"1540","1460":"1460","about 1475":"umbes 1475","1480":"1480","7 Dec 1487":"7. detsember 1487","1490":"1490","Ireland":"Iirimaa","Thomond, Ireland":"County Clare, Iirimaa","Castle Chomhaid, Burren, Thomond, Ireland":"Boirinn, County Clare, Iirimaa","Rathkeale, Munster, Ierland":"Munster, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"1460–1503":"1460–1503","1520–Male":"1520–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1460–1487":"1460–1487","1475–1540":"1475–1540","1490–Male":"1490–Kuollut","1503":"1503","1487":"1487","1520":"1520","1475":"1475","1540":"1540","1460":"1460","about 1475":"noin 1475","1480":"1480","7 Dec 1487":"7. joulukuuta 1487","1490":"1490","Ireland":"Irlanti","Thomond, Ireland":"County Clare, Irlanti","Castle Chomhaid, Burren, Thomond, Ireland":"Boirinn, County Clare, Irlanti","Rathkeale, Munster, Ierland":"Munster, Irlanti"},"fr":{"1460–1503":"1460–1503","1520–Male":"1520–Décédé","–Male":"Décédé","1460–1487":"1460–1487","1475–1540":"1475–1540","1490–Male":"1490–Décédé","1503":"1503","1487":"1487","1520":"1520","1475":"1475","1540":"1540","1460":"1460","about 1475":"environ 1475","1480":"1480","7 Dec 1487":"7 décembre 1487","1490":"1490","Ireland":"Irlande","Thomond, Ireland":"County Clare, Irlande","Castle Chomhaid, Burren, Thomond, Ireland":"Boirinn, County Clare, Irlande","Rathkeale, Munster, Ierland":"Munster, Irlande","lifeS